Correlation between Salary and Other Variables

Ching Yi Lam

9/30/2024

1 Introduction

In this report, we investigate the some of the variables in this dataset. We will perform the exploratory data analysis, and running the regression models to find if there is any correlation between each others.

2 Description of Data

This Human Resources data set comprises a range of information from employees. It features variables such as names, DOBs, age, gender, marital status, date of hire, reasons for termination, department, whether they are active or terminated, position title, pay rate, manager name and performance score, absences, most recent performance review date, and employee engagement score. This data set is collected from my professor’s teaching data repository. There are 36 variables and 311 records. It has 8 missing values from the variable of manager ID but other than this variable, there is no missing value. A detailed description of the variables is given below:

Employee Name: Employee’s full name.

EmpID: Employee ID is unique to each employee.

MarriedID: The person is married or not. It has values a 0 or 1. 0 indicates they are not married, and 1 indicates they are married.

MaritalStatusID: Marital status code that matches the text field MaritalDesc.

GenderID: The person is Male or Female. It has value a 0 or 1. 0 indicates Female, and 1 indicates Male.

EmpStatusID: Employment status code that matches text field EmploymentStatus.

DeptID: Department ID code that matches the department the employee works in.

PerfScoreID: Performance Score code that matches the employee’s most recent performance score.

FromDiversityJobFairID: To show if the employee was sourced from the Diversity job fair. It has values a 0 or 1. 0 indicates no, and 1 indicates yes.

Salary: The person’s yearly salary in US Dollars.

Termd: To show if the employee has been terminated. It has values a 0 or 1. 0 indicates no, and 1 indicates yes.

PositionID: An integer indicating the person’s position.

Position: The text name/title of the position the person has.

State: The state that the person lives in.

Zip: The zip code for the employee.

DOB: Date of Birth for the employee.

Sex: M is Male, and F is Female.

MaritalDesc: The marital status of the person (divorced, single, widowed, separated, etc)

CitizenDesc: Label for whether the person is a Citizen or Eligible Non-Citizen.

HispanicLatino: Yes or No field for whether the employee is Hispanic or Latino.

RaceDesc: Description/text of the race the person identifies with.

DateofHire: Date the person was hired.

DateofTermination: Date the person was terminated, only populated, if, in fact, Termd = 1.

TermReason: A text reason/description for why the person was terminated.

EmploymentStatus: A description/category of the person’s employment status. Anyone currently working full time = Active.

Department: Name of the department that the person works in.

ManageName: The name of the person’s immediate manager.

ManagerID: A unique identifier for each manager.

RecruitmentSource: The name of the recruitment source where the employee was recruited from.

PerformanceScore: Performance Score text/category (Fully Meets, Partially Meets, PIP, Exceeds)

EngagementSurvey: Results from the last engagement survey, managed by our external partner.

EmpSatisfaction: A basic satisfaction score between 1 and 5, as reported on a recent employee satisfaction survey. 1 is the lowest score and 5 is the highest score.

SpecialProjectsCount: The number of special projects that the employee worked on during the last 6 months.

LastPerformanceReviewDate: The most recent date of the person’s last performance review.

DaysLateLast30: The number of times that the employee was late to work during the last 30 days.

Absences: The number of times the employee was absent from work.

A copy of this publicly available data is stored at https://pengdsci.github.io/datasets/HRDataset/HRDatasetV14.csv.

3 Statistical Regression Modeling

3.1 Linear Regression Models

To find whether if there is a correlation between the variables Salary, Sex, Race Description and Department. The purpose of this analysis will be an association analysis. The data set has sufficient information to address the question.

  • Initial model

The following initial model includes 3 predictor variables: Sex, Race Description, and Department. The residual plots demonstrate the following patterns.

ini.model = lm(Salary ~ Sex + RaceDesc + Department, data = hr)   
par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar=c(2,3,2,2))
plot(ini.model)

Next, we will carry the Box-Cox transformation to identify a potential power transformation of the response variable: Salary.

library(MASS)
boxcox(Salary ~ Sex + RaceDesc + Department, 
       data = hr, 
       lambda = seq(-1, 1.5, length = 10), 
       xlab=expression(paste(lambda)))
title(main = "Box-Cox Transformation: 95% CI of lambda",
      col.main = "navy", cex.main = 0.9)

Since both 0 and 1 are in the 95% confidence interval of λ, there is no need to perform the power transformation. By the optimal λ is closer to 0,we try to perform the log transformation to see whether there will be some improvement of the initial model.

transform.model = lm(log(Salary) ~ Sex * RaceDesc * Department , data  = hr)
par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar = c(2,2,2,2))
plot(transform.model)

The above residual plots indicate an improvement in model fit. We will use the transformed response to build the final model.

  • Final model

We can see that there is one interaction effect is significant in the model. In the next model, we use the automatic variable selection method to find the final model.

transform.model = lm(log(Salary)~Sex*RaceDesc*Department, data = hr)
final.model =  step(transform.model, direction = "forward", trace = 0)
backward.model =  step(transform.model, direction = "backward", trace = 0)

Now we have 1 candidate models to select from. We extract the coefficient of determination (R^2) of the candidate model.

r.ini.model = summary(ini.model)$r.squared
r.transfd.model = summary(transform.model)$r.squared
r.final.model = summary(final.model)$r.squared
r.backward.model = summary(backward.model)$r.squared
##
Rsquare = cbind(ini.model = r.ini.model, transfd.model = r.transfd.model, backward.model = r.backward.model, 
                final.model = r.final.model)
kable(Rsquare, caption="Coefficients of correlation of the candidate model")
Coefficients of correlation of the candidate model
ini.model transfd.model backward.model final.model
0.5039231 0.5426979 0.5082834 0.5426979

We used forward selection to choose the best model. The final model with the log transformation and forward selection: R^2 = 0.5427. This is the highest out of all models so we choose this as the final model.

3.2 Logistic Regression Analysis

The purpose of this logistic regression analysis is to find out if we can use the predictor variables to predict our response variable: Salary. The purpose of this analysis will be a predictive analysis. We will create a new variable called SalaryID.

The response variable: SalaryID - It shows the salary of the employees in US Dollar. 0 indicates the employee’s salary is below the median = 62810, and 1 indicates the employee’s salary is above median.

Predictor variables:

  • Sex
  • Department
  • Hispanic or Latino
  • Marital Description
  • Citizen Description
  • Race Description
  • Absences
  • Days Late Last 30 Days
  • Engagement Survey

Here below we are trying to build the initial model.

  • Build an Initial Model
library(dplyr)

  mutate(SalaryID = ifelse(Salary >= 62810, 1, 0))

                    + RaceDesc + Absences + DaysLateLast30 + EngagementSurvey, family = binomial, data = hr)

The p-value in the above significance test table are all bigger than 0.5. Then, we will search for the best model by dropping some of the insignificant predictor variables. We will use an automatic variable procedure to search for the final model.

  • Automatic Variable Selection

We assume Department, Engagement Survey, and Absences are practically important, we want to include these three variables in the final model regardless of their statistical significance.

In summary, we define two models: the full model and the reduced model. The final best model will be the model between the full and reduced models. The summary table of significant tests is given below.

full.model = initial.model 
reduced.model = glm(SalaryID ~  + Department + EngagementSurvey + Absences , family = binomial, data = hr)
final.model =  step(full.model, 
                    scope=list(lower=formula(reduced.model),upper=formula(full.model)),
                    data = hr, 
                    direction = "backward",
                    trace = 0)   
final.model.coef = summary(final.model)$coef
kable(final.model.coef , caption = "Summary table of significant tests")

  • Interpretation - Predictive analysis

The summary table contains the three practically important variables Department, Engagement Survey, and Absences. We used backward selection to choose the best model. However, all of the variables do not achieve statistical significance. The p-value of Department IT/IS and Department Production have a smaller value than the other variables but they are still higher than alpha = 0.05. Department: IT/IS is positively associated with the response variable. Department: Production is negatively associated with the response variable.

In summary, this logistic regression model analysis cannot find the employee’s salary is above or below median based on the department, engagement survey, and absences because all the p-value of the variables are not statistically significant.

4 Predictive Modeling

4.1 Prediction Linear Regression

hr_clean = na.omit(hr)  # delete all records with missing values
##
n = dim(hr_clean)[1]     # sample size
obs.ID = 1:n            # randomize obs ID
n.train = round(0.8*n)  # training data size

shuffled.id = sample(obs.ID, 
                          n, 
                          replace = FALSE)  # randomizing the observation IDs 
shuffled.hr = na.omit(hr_clean[shuffled.id, ])   # randomizing the data set
# Two-way split for training and testing data sets
train.data = shuffled.hr[1:n.train,]         # training data
test.data = shuffled.hr[(n.train + 1):n, ]   # testing data
##
n.fold = round(n.train/5)-1    # size of 5-fold splitting, -1 to guarantee that
                               # 5*foldsize <= train.data size
## 5-fold cross-validation: iterative process with a for-loop
##
MSE.M1 = rep(0,5)
MSE.M2 = rep(0,5)
##
for (i in 1:5){
  valid.id = ((i-1)*n.fold+1):(i*n.fold)    # obs ID for validating fold 
  cross.train = train.data[-valid.id, ]
  cross.valid = train.data[valid.id,]
  ## Building the two models
  M1 = lm(Salary ~ PositionID + DeptID  , data  = cross.train)
  M2 = lm(Salary ~PositionID +  DeptID + ManagerID, data  = cross.train)
  ## Predicting bodyMass with validate fold
  predM1 = predict(M1, newdata = cross.valid)
  predM2 = predict(M2, newdata = cross.valid)
  ##
  MSE.M1[i] = mean((predM1 - cross.valid$Salary)^2)
  MSE.M2[i] = mean((predM2 - cross.valid$Salary)^2)
 }
 MSE.1 = mean(MSE.M1)
 MSE.2 = mean(MSE.M2)
 ### Visualize the MSE 
 plot(1:5, MSE.M1, type = "l", 
      xlim =c(0,6),
      ylim = c(100000, 50000+max(MSE.M1)),
      ylab = "MSE (g)",
      xlab = "Iterations 1 to 5",
      lwd = 2,
      col = "navy",
      main = "Performance Evaluation via 5-fold Cross Validation",
      cex.main = 0.8)
 points(1:5, MSE.M1, pch = 19, col = "navy")
 lines(1:5, MSE.M2, lwd = 2, col = "darkred")
 points(1:5, MSE.M2, pch = 19, col = "darkred")
 legend("topright", c(paste("M1 Avg. MSE: ", round(MSE.1)), paste("M2 Avg. MSE: ",round(MSE.2))),
        col=c("navy", "darkred"),
        pch = rep(19,2), 
        lwd = rep(2,2),
        cex = 0.6,
        bty = "n")

Cross-validation for evaluating predictive performance of linear regression models

From part 4, we expect that the explanatory variables are not the best predictor of the salary so we expect large MSE for both models. Between the two models, model M2 has a smaller fold-wise MSE. This means that model M2 has a better predictive performance. Therefore, model M2 is recommended for practical prediction.

M2.final = lm(Salary ~PositionID +  DeptID + ManagerID, data  = train.data)
predM2.final = predict(M2.final, newdata = test.data)
MSE.M2.final = mean((predM2.final - test.data$Salary)^2)

4.2 Logistic Predictive Modeling

We use 10-fold cross-validation in this model.

nn = dim(hr)[1]
train.id = sample(1:nn, round(nn*0.7), replace = FALSE) 
trainDat = hr[train.id,]
testDat = hr[-train.id,]
## each fold has 2326 observations
##
AUC.vec = rep(0,5)
color=c("#002642","#840032","#432534", "#c44900", "#0b7a75")
##
for(i in 1:5){
  ID = ((i-1)*43+1):(i*43)
  valid = as.data.frame(trainDat[ID,])
  train = as.data.frame(trainDat[-ID,])
  ##
  logit.model = glm(SalaryID ~ PositionID, family = binomial(link = logit), data = hr)
  newdata = data.frame(PositionID = valid$PositionID)
  pred.prob.train = predict.glm(logit.model, newdata, type = "response")
  ## we next use library {pROC}
  ## to calculate AUC
  prediction = pred.prob.train
  category = valid$SalaryID == 1
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  AUC.vec[i] = round(auc(ROCobj),4)
  if(i==1){
    plot((1-ROCobj$specificities),ROCobj$sensitivities,
         type="l",
         main="5-fold Cross-validated ROC",
         col=color[i], 
         xlab="1-specificty",
         ylab="sensitivity",
         lwd=1, 
         lty=1)
        segments(0,0,1,1, lty=2, col="red")
    } else{
    lines((1-ROCobj$specificities),ROCobj$sensitivities, col=color[i], lwd=1)
    }
}
